  "text_preview": "\"party\" American Sign Language (ASL) ASL University ► American Sign Language: \"party\" The sign PARTY can be done with either \"Y\" handshapes or with \"P\" handshapes. A colleague emailed me to say that \"PARTY\" and \"PLAY\" are distinguished by differences in the movement of the signs: PLAY: Arms stay stationary, wrists twist. PARTY: Wrists stay straight, arms swing back and forth. Of course, as is my way, I immediately started surveying a large number of skilled signers as to how they did the sign PARTY. After quite a bit of research it seems fairly certain to me that both the \"swinging\" version and the \"twisting\" version are in widespread use and as time goes on the versions of \"PARTY\" that use a twisting movement are becoming increasingly popular. An interesting note told to me by one of my i"
}
